name: SplayTreeMap
comment:
A dart-core.Map of objects that can be ordered relative to each other.

The map is based on a self-balancing binary tree. It allows most operations in amortized logarithmic time.

Keys of the map are compared using the compare function passed in the constructor. If that is omitted, the objects are assumed to be dart-core.Comparable, and are compared using their dart-core.Comparable.compareTo method. Non-comparable objects (including null) will not work as keys in that case.

To allow calling operator, dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.remove or dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.containsKey with objects that are not supported by the compare function, an extra isValidKey predicate function can be supplied. This function is tested before using the compare function on an argument value that may not be a dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.K value. If omitted, the isValidKey function defaults to testing if the value is a dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.K.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no key-value pair in the map.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one key-value pair in the map.

length.name: length
length.comment: The number of key-value pairs in the map.

keys.name: keys
keys.comment:
The keys of this.

The returned iterable has efficient length and contains operations, based on dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.length and dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.containsKey of the map.

The order of iteration is defined by the individual Map implementation, but must be consistent between changes to the map.

values.name: values
values.comment:
The values of this.

The values are iterated in the order of their corresponding keys. This means that iterating dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.keys and dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.values in parrallel will provided matching pairs of keys and values.

The returned iterable has an efficient length method based on the dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.length of the map.

from.name: from
from.comment: Creates a dart-collection.SplayTreeMap that contains all key value pairs of dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-from.other.

fromIterable.name: fromIterable
fromIterable.comment:
Creates a dart-collection.SplayTreeMap where the keys and values are computed from the dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterable.iterable.

For each element of the dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterable.iterable this constructor computes a key/value pair, by applying dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterable.key and dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterable.value respectively.

The keys of the key/value pairs do not need to be unique. The last occurrence of a key will simply overwrite any previous value.

If no values are specified for dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterable.key and dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterable.value the default is the identity function.

fromIterables.name: fromIterables
fromIterables.comment:
Creates a dart-collection.SplayTreeMap associating the given dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.keys to dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.values.

This constructor iterates over dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.keys and dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.values and maps each element of dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.keys to the corresponding element of dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.values.

If dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.SplayTreeMap-fromIterables.keys contains the same object multiple times, the last occurrence overwrites the previous value.

It is an error if the two dart-core.Iterables don't have the same length.

[].comment: Returns the value for the given dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.[].key or null if dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.[].key is not in the map. Because null values are supported, one should either use dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.containsKey to distinguish between an absent key and a null value, or use the dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.putIfAbsent method.

[]=.comment:
Associates the dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.[]=.key with the given dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.[]=.value.

If the key was already in the map, its associated value is changed. Otherwise the key-value pair is added to the map.

remove.name: remove
remove.comment: Removes the association for the given dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.remove.key. Returns the value for dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.remove.key in the map or null if dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.remove.key is not in the map. Note that values can be null and a returned null value does not always imply that the key is absent.

putIfAbsent.name: putIfAbsent
putIfAbsent.comment:
If dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.putIfAbsent.key is not associated to a value, calls dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent and updates the map by mapping dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.putIfAbsent.key to the value returned by dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent. Returns the value in the map.

Map<String, int> scores = {'Bob': 36};
for (var key in ['Bob', 'Rohan', 'Sophena']) {
  scores.putIfAbsent(key, () => key.length);
}
scores['Bob'];      // 36
scores['Rohan'];    //  5
scores['Sophena'];  //  7

The code that dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent executes must not add or remove keys.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Adds all key-value pairs of dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.addAll.other to this map.

If a key of dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.addAll.other is already in this map, its value is overwritten.

The operation is equivalent to doing this[key] = value for each key and associated value in other. It iterates over dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.addAll.other, which must therefore not change during the iteration.

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment:
Applies dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.forEach.f to each {key, value} pair of the map.

Adding or removing keys from the map during iteration is not allowed.

clear.name: clear
clear.comment:
Removes all pairs from the map.

After this, the map is empty.

containsKey.name: containsKey
containsKey.comment: Returns true if this map contains the given key.

containsValue.name: containsValue
containsValue.comment: Returns true if this map contains the given value.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

firstKey.name: firstKey
firstKey.comment: Get the first key in the map. Returns null if the map is empty.

lastKey.name: lastKey
lastKey.comment: Get the last key in the map. Returns null if the map is empty.

lastKeyBefore.name: lastKeyBefore
lastKeyBefore.comment: Get the last key in the map that is strictly smaller than dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.lastKeyBefore.key. Returns null if no key was not found.

firstKeyAfter.name: firstKeyAfter
firstKeyAfter.comment: Get the first key in the map that is strictly larger than dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.firstKeyAfter.key. Returns null if no key was not found.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-collection.SplayTreeMap.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
